</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="488" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1053,1908]" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1666,1692]" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">Remarks.</emphasis>
Some extant members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Colless" authorityYear="1962" box="[622,760,1666,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Perissommatidae" genus="Perissomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[622,760,1666,1691]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">Perissomma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also distinct from each other in the size of the male ninth tergite (
<bibRefCitation author="Colless, D. H." box="[237,388,1701,1728]" pageId="7" pageNumber="488" pagination="719 - 728" refId="ref6928" refString="Colless, D. H. (1969) The genus Perissomma (Diptera: Perissommatidae), with new species from Australia and Chile. Australian Journal of Zoology, 17, 719 - 728. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / ZO 9690719" type="journal article" year="1969">Colless 1969</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1053,1908]" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">
In the 
<typeStatus box="[270,368,1737,1763]" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lukashevich &amp; Blagoderov, 2020" authorityName="Lukashevich &amp; Blagoderov" authorityYear="2020" box="[404,512,1738,1764]" class="Insecta" family="Perissommatidae" genus="Collessomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gnoma" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[404,512,1738,1764]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">C. gnoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[519,692,1738,1764]" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[519,692,1738,1764]" pageId="7" pageNumber="488" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
the apical portion of the abdomen is bent onto the dorsal side (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1924,1949]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,166,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[203,1385,166,1904]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. C.gnoma gen. et sp. nov. A–C. Paratype PIN No. 5340/2982, male. A, B. Ventral and dorsal view of head (part and counterpart). C. Leg. D, E. Holotype PIN No. 5026/201, male, total view and terminalia. F–H. Paratype PIN No. 5340/2981, female. F. Antenna. G. Cerci. H. Total view. Scale bars 200 μm (A, B, C, E, F, G), 1 mm (D, H)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3602684" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3602684/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
). Probably the dorsoflexion is facultative because it is absent in another male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lukashevich &amp; Blagoderov, 2020" authorityName="Lukashevich &amp; Blagoderov" authorityYear="2020" box="[1100,1251,1773,1799]" class="Insecta" family="Perissommatidae" genus="Collessomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1100,1251,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">Collessomma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<typeStatus box="[1265,1363,1773,1799]" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">holotype</typeStatus>
of the type species (
<figureCitation box="[306,398,1809,1835]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,174,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male of Collessomma sibirica gen. et sp. nov. A–E. holotype PIN No. 5340/1681. A. Total view. B. Terminalia. C, D. Head, dorsal and ventral view. E.Anterior part of wing with pterostigma. F. PIN No. 5026/1558, head with facets of different size. Scale bars 1 mm (A), 200 μm (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3602678" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3602678/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="488">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Unfortunately, now we have only two undoubted males with termimalia preserved in our disposal, and it is not enough for conclusions—it may be a disarticulated part. Dorsoflexion is widely distributed among 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cumming &amp; Wood" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[234,318,1881,1907]" kingdom="Plantae" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="488" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
but was not recorded in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Colless" authorityYear="1962" box="[595,786,1881,1907]" class="Insecta" family="Perissommatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Perissommatidae</taxonomicName>
before.
</paragraph>
